16 (2) Taxpayer funded meal and snack programs provided to children in public schools
17 should support, not hinder, a child's cognitive and behavioral development. School meals
18 and snacks should prioritize nourishment to promote the health and well-being of children
19 and their abilities to meet educational expectations.
20 SECTION 3.
21 Part 3 of Article 16 of Chapter 2 of Title 20 of the Official Code of Georgia Annotated,
22 relating to student health, is amended by adding a new Code section to read as follows:
23 "20-2-779.5.
24 (a) As used in this Code section, the term 'synthetic dye' means:
25 (1) Blue 1;
26 (2) Blue 2;
27 (3) Green 3;
28 (4) Red 3;
29 (5) Red 40;
30 (6) Yellow 5; or
31 (7) Yellow 6.
32 (b) Beginning in the 2026-2027 school year, no public primary or secondary school shall
33 serve or sell, or allow a third party to serve or sell, any food or beverage that contains
34 synthetic dye on school grounds during the regular school day or as part of a school
35 breakfast program.
36 (c) This Code section shall not be construed so as to prohibit the parent or guardian of a
37 student at a public primary or secondary school from providing food or beverages that
38 contain synthetic dye to such parent's or guardian's child or for a school or classroom event.
39 (d) The Department of Education shall develop a standardized form that public primary
40 and secondary schools may use to certify that such schools are in compliance with the
41 provisions of this Code section. The Department of Education shall maintain a list of
